==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spoke
<hw>Spoke</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>spoke</ets>,
<ets>spake</ets>, AS. <ets>sp⟦amac⟧ca</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>speek</ets>, LG. <ets>speke</ets>, OHG. <ets>speihha</ets>, G.
<ets>speiche</ets>. ⟦root⟧170. Cf. <er>Spike</er> a nail.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The radius or ray of a wheel; one of the small bars
which are inserted in the hub, or nave, and which serve to support the
rim or felly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A projecting handle of a steering
wheel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A rung, or round, of a ladder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A contrivance for fastening the wheel of a vehicle,
to prevent it from turning in going down a hill.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To put a spoke in one's wheel</b></col>, <cd>to thwart or
obstruct one in the execution of some design.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spoke</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spoke
<hw>Spoke</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spoked</conjf> <pr>(sp⟦omac⟧kt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spoking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To furnish with spokes, as a
wheel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spoken</ent>⟦br⟧
